ekjhe4devnaffqctyxgsqX;bafyreidc3prllj4ztbr5k23wtevkppt3f3gdfgf7diwik3ql5jhara7cvmX;bafyreiaoncyedwphzzqvkvrc6qxfcpb5jaxejkuig3dvwtvt3ri67zbheyX;bafyreidinzmqz3wbgkgkdkdtmrsn7hq6wgg6ng5dmvxpzs7gne6u6k7c44X;bafyreie25dy7ggxrqpimtyztc3fca3xse4gysgq5ls6h35jxlrsmuvu6xaX;bafyreicyq45nqwk47bdzw72nhpgo3dmjuwhuj7pwxdqzhii2gshhekt3bmX;bafyreihf65umlbbvufq5mam4g2fkzla3afveruwq4aee5rlisaqyhn4dbeX;bafyreifcpsxduezxd4awedh7vew6m4mu77l56ctcgneu5ot2kfp5mef3ymX;bafyreifcxybgwqrqn7a3xeasnmxin4zqhbdpftpbqeowvefa54gf2nltbaX;bafyreiclokyfvkzjl5wn4tjmbfi7n56p7pwwjl2c5xbrxjeqveqc2u7ryuX;bafyreia3vxokqo5zs4n7f5ex7tdqtvxgpqerccboi65ctxqwz3lyhviag4X;bafyreiait6vk7nsqce5i3puxqbwmsxjhgoadtdtdyud2poiflilvujt56yX;bafyreiarx4dj7zothsrhh65w22hvm4alx44ry6c5lnvfbzbyesrm22rrmiX;bafyreig5744qvxkft4d532ufauqtnj3cbrn5ttuigipheywdvkv5r65j5qX;bafyreiardfv7sqa2d3wfsvjnkutemx54lbfa52jkjrtalhttxx7duwhlnugversion;bafyreieaogdoe2zj5gudfhmogfcjwnt4rjlzcb7u4ayurfhah6x2ighunq™!ĮdtypewPhilosophicalHypothesisetitlexKPerceptual Frames as Intelligence Multipliers (The Different OS Hypothesis)fdomainlEpistemologyfproofsÉ§dtypeianecdotalireferencexJPersonal accounts from artists, scientists, and meditators across culturesjconfidenceŻ?Ť␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxúObserved pattern across multiple domains: altered perceptual states reveal different cognitive patterns and creative insights inaccessible in baseline state§dtypektheoreticalireferencexsFriston, K. (2010). The free-energy principle: a unified brain theory? Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 11(2), 127-138.jconfidenceŻ?ťôôôôôökdescriptionxĽPredictive processing framework suggests that perception is an active inference process where prior expectations shape what is perceived - altering these priors changes perceptual reality§dtypeiempiricalireferencex∑Carhart-Harris, R.L., et al. (2014). The entropic brain: a theory of conscious states informed by neuroimaging research with psychedelic drugs. Frontiers in Human Neuroscience, 8, 20.jconfidenceŻ?Ťű¬Ź\(Ųkdescriptionx¶Research on psychedelics shows increased neural entropy and altered connectivity patterns correlating with enhanced cognitive flexibility and creative problem-solvinggformulax7IQ_effective = IQ_baseline √ó P(perceptual_os, context)hhuman_idx-perceptual_frames_as_intelligence_multipliershmetadataßgcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionjsupersedesx;bafyreibz3cxr7vdqgn7pqk7lq7wblmpswdjneqc5gkiiyzcmuulq2d4h5qocertainty_scoreŻ?Ž333333isubdomainx)Cognitive Science / Consciousness Studiesjdefinitiony\Intelligence is not fixed but is filtered through the operating system of perception. Different states of consciousness - whether induced by meditation, psychedelics, flow states, or neurodivergent cognition - change the perceptual OS, enabling different pattern recognition capabilities and revealing what was previously invisible to the observer.lextra_fields®hcategoryx.Metaphysics / Epistemology / Cognitive Sciencekattributionx6Hieros-CADMIES / DS / Alan Watts (posthumous honorary)klimitationsxęHighly subjective; difficult to quantify objectively. Individual variation in response to altered states. Requires further empirical validation through controlled studies.lapplicationsĄvCreativity enhancementtTherapeutic contextsvEducation optimizationxProblem-solving frameworksninsight_originx@Collaborative dialogue between human and artificial intelligencenkey_referencesĄjJames 1902kHuxley 1954jWatts 1957sCarhart-Harris 2014rhistorical_contextyThe hypothesis draws from William James' varieties of religious experience, Aldous Huxley's 'doors of perception', Alan Watts' comparative philosophy, and contemporary psychedelic research. It synthesizes Eastern contemplative traditions with Western cognitive science.treference_os_analogyxYEveryone understands operating systems - this makes complex cognitive concepts accessiblemlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsĄupredictive_processingjenactivismrneurophenomenologywcollective_intelligencemprerequisitesÉtcognitive_psychologyrphilosophy_of_minduconsciousness_studiesmrelationshipsĘjrelated_toĀx!information_is_physical_principlekbuilds_uponĀupredictive_processingnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀxfixed_intelligence_theoryprelated_conceptsÖtcognitive_plasticitynneurodiversityupredictive_processingvstate_dependent_memoryxaltered_states_of_consciousnessqdifficulty_levels£fexpertykThe observer's perceptual apparatus - modified by substances, practices, or neurodivergent conditions - fundamentally shapes phenomenological reality and pattern detection. This suggests that collective intelligence emerges from diverse perceptual OS configurations, and that epistemic humility requires acknowledging the limits of one's current perceptual frame.hbeginnerx≥Your mindset and state of consciousness changes what you can see and understand. What you perceive depends on your 'operating system' - change the OS, change what becomes visible.lintermediatexŗCognitive frameworks and altered states act as perceptual OS filters that enable different patterns to emerge. Intelligence is not a fixed quantity but a function of the observer's perceptual apparatus and its current state.;bafyreib3eztwxtsbq66e6sihfkresdy4sqezvefytqnqzp22hlwvqppatuőĮdtypemScientificLawetitlexLaw of Conservation of EnergyfdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexßNoether, E. (1918). Invariante Variationsprobleme. Nachrichten von der Gesellschaft der Wissenschaften zu G√∂ttingen, Mathematisch-Physikalische Klasse, 1918, 235-257.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxsNoether's theorem establishes conservation of energy as a consequence of time-translation symmetry in physical laws§dtypelexperimentalireferencexvJoule, J.P. (1850). On the Mechanical Equivalent of Heat. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, 140, 61-82.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxuCountless experiments across physics, chemistry, and engineering have validated energy conservation to high precisiongformulax!őĒE_system + őĒE_surroundings = 0hhuman_idvconservation_of_energyhmetadataßgcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionjsupersedesx;bafyreiaeqlqeykyu33kggmf5zwd5wn6yanecibwdxlu2t5o6jaxk3jeswyocertainty_scoreŻ?ÔģzŠGģisubdomainsClassical Mechanicsjdefinitionx≥Energy cannot be created or destroyed within an isolated system; it can only transform from one form to another. The total energy of an isolated system remains constant over time.lextra_fieldsßjdiscovererxDJulius Robert von Mayer, James Prescott Joule, Hermann von HelmholtzklimitationsxŚEnergy conservation in general relativity is subtle; global energy conservation breaks down in expanding spacetime (cosmology). Virtual particles in quantum field theory temporarily violate conservation but average out over time.lapplicationsĄpPower generationjBallisticslAstrophysicsoThermal systemsndiscovery_year2nkey_referencesÉlNoether 1918jJoule 1850nHelmholtz 1847qrelated_equationsÉhE = mc¬≤kőĒU = Q - WidE/dt = 0rhistorical_contextxŁThe concept evolved through the work of Leibniz, Joule, Helmholtz, and Mayer in the 1840s-1850s, culminating in the first law of thermodynamics. Noether's theorem (1918) provided the deep mathematical foundation linking conservation laws to symmetries.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉpnoethers_theoremxfirst_law_of_thermodynamicsuhamiltonian_mechanicsmprerequisitesālnewtons_lawsswork_energy_theoremmrelationshipsĘkbuilds_uponĀvnewtons_laws_of_motionkcontradictsÄnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsÉxconservation_of_momentumtconservation_of_massxfirst_law_of_thermodynamicsqdifficulty_levels£fexpertxűEnergy conservation emerges from time-translation symmetry via Noether's theorem. In general relativity, energy conservation requires careful formulation due to curved spacetime, but in flat spacetime and local inertial frames, it holds exactly.hbeginnerxôEnergy can change forms (like from motion to heat) but the total amount always stays the same. You can't create energy from nothing or make it disappear.lintermediatex•The total energy of any isolated system remains constant. Energy transforms between kinetic, potential, thermal, chemical, and other forms, but the sum is invariant.;bafyreia4gz2si7tfvnbln4qkk5qy44hbr4xcdgccb42nqkrno5txi53xnm…ĮdtypesScientificPrincipleetitlex!Information is Physical PrinciplefdomaingPhysicsfproofsÉ§dtypektheoreticalireferencexäLandauer, R. (1961). Irreversibility and Heat Generation in the Computing Process. IBM Journal of Research and Development, 5(3), 183-191.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxtLandauer's principle establishes the physicality of information through energy dissipation in irreversible computing§dtypelexperimentalireferencexcB√©rut, A., et al. (2012). Experimental verification of Landauer's principle. Nature, 483, 187-189.jconfidenceŻ?Ū¬Ź\(ű√kdescriptionx]Experimental verification of Landauer's principle using colloidal particles and optical traps§dtypektheoreticalireferencex~Bennett, C.H. (1982). The thermodynamics of computation‚ÄĒa review. International Journal of Theoretical Physics, 21, 905-940.jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxkMaxwell's demon thought experiment demonstrates that information acquisition has thermodynamic consequencesgformulax4E ‚Č• kT ln(2) per bit erased (Landauer's principle)hhuman_idx!information_is_physical_principlehmetadataßgcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionjsupersedesx;bafyreidlyqiioh3hzjuhenb65rf7ys44rmkyzr2mcnjfneax3nasiojzniocertainty_scoreŻ?ÓffffffisubdomainrInformation TheoryjdefinitionxķInformation is not abstract or immaterial but is always encoded in physical states of systems. Every bit of information corresponds to a physical configuration, and information processing requires physical resources including energy, space, and time.lextra_fields®jdiscoverermRolf LandauerklimitationsxĚApplies to macroscopic systems; quantum information processing may have different constraints. The kT ln(2) bound is a minimum - real systems dissipate more.lapplicationsĄxComputing efficiency limitsqQuantum computingnNanotechnologyxInformation thermodynamicsndiscovery_year©nkey_referencesÉmLandauer 1961lBennett 1982rB√©rut et al. 2012qrelated_equationsÉpőĒE ‚Č• kT ln(2)nS = k_B ln(ő©)qI = H(X) - H(X|Y)rhistorical_contexty␀The principle emerged from Landauer's 1961 insight connecting computation to thermodynamics, resolving Maxwell's demon paradox. Bennett (1982) extended the work, showing that only logically irreversible operations (like erasure) require energy dissipation.xphilosophical_implicationx[Information cannot be separated from its physical substrate - mind and matter are entangledmlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsĄslandauers_principlenmaxwells_demonqquantum_computingpbekenstein_boundmprerequisitesÉtbasic_thermodynamicsgentropysclassical_mechanicsmrelationshipsĘjrelated_toĀventropy_thermodynamicskcontradictsĀqfundamental_unitynschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsĄslandauers_principlenmaxwells_demonnthermodynamicssquantum_informationqdifficulty_levels£fexperty%The physicality of information bridges thermodynamics and computation, establishing fundamental limits on computing and connecting Shannon entropy to thermodynamic entropy. Landauer's principle provides the quantitative link: erasing one bit of information dissipates at least kT ln(2) energy.hbeginnerxĻInformation has to be stored somewhere physical - you can't have information without something physical to hold it. Even computer data exists as electrical charges or magnetic patterns.lintermediatex©Information is tied to physical states; erasing information generates heat and is a physical process, not abstract. This connects computation directly to thermodynamics.;bafyreiho6xxraamgnfar6ke3sbryw453xqliqvuveleg25xbfsxw5h6vriżĮdtypevPhilosophicalPrincipleetitlex&Occam's Razor (Principle of Parsimony)fdomainjPhilosophyfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexeSolomonoff, R.J. (1964). A formal theory of inductive inference. Information and Control, 7(1), 1-22.jconfidenceŻ?Ž333333kdescriptionxÄSolomonoff's theory of inductive inference provides mathematical justification: simpler hypotheses have higher prior probability§dtypeipracticalireferencexńForster, M., & Sober, E. (1994). How to tell when simpler, more unified, or less ad hoc theories will provide more accurate predictions. British Journal for the Philosophy of Science, 45(1), 1-35.jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxkAcross scientific disciplines, parsimony has proven effective in model selection and preventing overfittinggformulax8P(H|E) ‚ąĚ 2^{-K(H)} where K(H) is Kolmogorov complexityhhuman_idloccams_razorhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕisubdomaintLogic / Epistemologyjdefinitionx≥Among competing hypotheses, the one with the fewest assumptions should be selected. Other things being equal, simpler explanations are more likely to be correct than complex ones.lextra_fields¶gcenturyd14thkattributionqWilliam of OckhamklimitationsxäNot a logical proof; simplicity does not guarantee truth. Can be subjective (what counts as 'simpler'?). May discard necessary complexity.lapplicationsĄsScientific modelingqMedical diagnosisoSoftware designvCriminal investigationnkey_referencesÉnOckham 14th c.oSolomonoff 1964tForster & Sober 1994rhistorical_contextx†Attributed to William of Ockham (c. 1287-1347), though similar ideas appear in Aristotle, Ptolemy, and Aquinas. The term 'Occam's Razor' first appeared in 1852.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉxminimum_description_lengthxalgorithmic_information_theoryomodel_selectionmprerequisitesÉrbayesian_inferencerprobability_theoryuphilosophy_of_sciencemrelationshipsĘkbuilds_uponĀuobservational_paradoxkspecializesĀqnatural_selectionnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀnhickams_dictumprelated_conceptsÉubayesian_occams_razorxminimum_description_lengthwalgorithmic_probabilityqdifficulty_levels£fexperty#Occam's Razor finds formal justification in Bayesian probability (simpler hypotheses have higher prior probability) and algorithmic information theory (minimum description length principle). The razor is not a logical necessity but a pragmatic heuristic that has proven remarkably effective.hbeginnerxtWhen you have two explanations for something, the simpler one is usually right. Don't add unnecessary complications.lintermediatexĘOccam's Razor is a heuristic for choosing between competing hypotheses: prefer the one that makes fewer assumptions. It prevents overfitting and ad hoc reasoning.;bafyreihzppla5p25j7fpgu4yda4d6ieamrcph7wl6l3xdpvvsbdlas2i74ÝĮdtypemScientificLawetitlewNewton's Laws of MotionfdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypeiempiricalireferencex@Newton, I. (1687). Philosophi√¶ Naturalis Principia Mathematica.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxcCountless experiments from ballistics to orbital mechanics validate Newton's laws to high precision§dtypektheoreticalireferencex2Noether, E. (1918). Invariante Variationsprobleme.jconfidenceŻ?Ô\(ű¬Ź\kdescriptionxMLaws emerge from conservation principles and symmetries via Noether's theoremgformulax$F = dp/dt = m¬∑a; F‚āĀ‚āā = -F‚āā‚āĀhhuman_idvnewtons_laws_of_motionhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÔģzŠGģisubdomainsClassical Mechanicsjdefinitiony&Three fundamental laws describing the relationship between a body and the forces acting upon it: (1) Inertia: objects remain at rest or in uniform motion unless acted by force; (2) F=ma: force equals mass times acceleration; (3) Action-reaction: every action has an equal and opposite reaction.lextra_fields¶jdiscovererlIsaac Newtonklimitationsx|Fails at very small scales (quantum mechanics), very high speeds (relativity), and very strong gravity (general relativity).lapplicationsÖkEngineeringiAstronomyjBallisticshRoboticsnVehicle designndiscovery_yearónkey_referencesÉkNewton 1687lGalileo 1638lNoether 1918rhistorical_contextxĘPublished in Newton's Principia Mathematica (1687), synthesizing work of Galileo, Kepler, and Hooke. Revolutionized physics and enabled the Industrial Revolution.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉuhamiltonian_mechanicstlagrangian_mechanicsrspecial_relativitymprerequisitesÉgalgebraltrigonometrynbasic_calculusmrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsÖqnewtons_first_lawrnewtons_second_lawqnewtons_third_lawginertiahmomentumqdifficulty_levels£fexperty-Newton's laws are approximations valid for macroscopic objects at speeds much less than light. They emerge from more fundamental conservation principles via Noether's theorem: first law from momentum conservation, second from definition of force, third from conservation of momentum in closed systems.hbeginnerxĎThings move the way they do because of forces. An object at rest stays at rest. Force makes things accelerate. Every push has an equal push back.lintermediatex√Newton's three laws form the foundation of classical mechanics: inertia (objects resist changes to motion), F=ma (force determines acceleration), and action-reaction (forces come in equal pairs).;bafyreidi74jhvrmegdsihwi2goxqagrdrvozqdcyyk5n34w66qujnlcjayŐĮdtypetPhilosophicalProblemetitlex!The Hard Problem of ConsciousnessfdomainjPhilosophyfproofsā§dtypemphilosophicalireferencexMChalmers, D.J. (1996). The Conscious Mind: In Search of a Fundamental Theory.jconfidenceŻ?šŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxźZombie argument: conceivability of philosophical zombies (physically identical but lacking consciousness) suggests consciousness is non-physical§dtypemphilosophicalireferencexTJackson, F. (1982). Epiphenomenal Qualia. Philosophical Quarterly, 32(127), 127-136.jconfidenceŻ?śffffffkdescriptionxěKnowledge argument: Mary in the black-and-white room learns all physical facts but learns something new upon seeing red, showing non-physical knowledge existsgformula`hhuman_idxhard_problem_of_consciousnesshmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÓffffffisubdomainrPhilosophy of Mindjdefinitiony␀The problem of explaining why and how physical processes in the brain give rise to subjective experience (qualia). While 'easy problems' explain cognitive functions, the hard problem addresses why there is 'something it is like' to be a conscious organism.lextra_fields¶joriginatoruDavid Chalmers (term)klimitationsxrSome philosophers (Dennett, Churchland) argue the hard problem is a pseudo-problem arising from confused concepts.korigin_year lapplicationsÉpAI consciousnessmAnimal ethicsuClinical neurosciencenkey_referencesĄmChalmers 1996lJackson 1982jNagel 1974lLeibniz 1714rhistorical_contextx}Term coined by David Chalmers in 1994, though the problem dates back to Leibniz, Descartes, and earlier philosophers of mind.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉkpanpsychismxintegrated_information_theorywglobal_workspace_theorymprerequisitesÉrphilosophy_of_mindqcognitive_sciencesneuroscience_basicsmrelationshipsĘkcontradictsĀpschrodingers_catkspecializesĀfqualianschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÉweliminative_materialismkillusionismkpanpsychismprelated_conceptsĄfqualiauphilosophical_zombiesoexplanatory_gapqmind_body_problemqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyVThe hard problem stems from an explanatory gap between objective physical descriptions and subjective phenomenal consciousness. Possible resolutions include panpsychism (consciousness fundamental), dualism (non-physical properties), illusionism (consciousness an illusion), or acceptance of the problem as unsolvable within current paradigms.hbeginnerxoWe know the brain does things, but we don't know why it feels like something to be us. That's the hard problem.lintermediatexĻWhile we can explain how brains process information, we cannot explain why there is subjective experience. The hard problem persists as a fundamental challenge to reductive physicalism.;bafyreibih425mjit4lny2jpli3byrfxhnthqkcfbvlvmqif7hgmnylktwqÕĮdtypeqScientificConceptetitlegEntropyfdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexćBoltzmann, L. (1877). √úber die Beziehung zwischen dem zweiten Hauptsatze der mechanischen W√§rmetheorie und der Wahrscheinlichkeitsrechnung.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxNBoltzmann's entropy formula connects microscopic states to macroscopic entropy§dtypeiempiricalireferencex?Carnot, S. (1824). R√©flexions sur la puissance motrice du feu.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxeCountless experiments confirm the second law; perpetual motion machines of the second kind impossiblegformulax-S = k_B ln(ő©); dS ‚Č• 0 for isolated systemshhuman_idgentropyhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÔģzŠGģisubdomainx&Thermodynamics / Statistical MechanicsjdefinitionxÝA measure of disorder, randomness, or uncertainty in a system. In thermodynamics, entropy quantifies the number of microscopic configurations corresponding to a macroscopic state. The second law states entropy of an isolated system never decreases.lextra_fields¶jdiscovererx6Rudolf Clausius (term), Ludwig Boltzmann (statistical)klimitationsxrApplies to large systems; fluctuations possible at small scales. Definition ambiguous for non-equilibrium systems.lapplicationsÖlHeat enginesmRefrigerationrInformation theoryiCosmologyiChemistryndiscovery_yearInkey_referencesĄmClausius 1865nBoltzmann 1877lShannon 1948jGibbs 1902rhistorical_contextxĘTerm coined by Rudolf Clausius in 1865 from Greek 'őĶőĹŌĄŌĀőŅŌÄőĻőĪ' (transformation). Boltzmann's statistical interpretation (1877) revolutionized understanding.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉxsecond_law_of_thermodynamicssinformation_entropyxblack_hole_thermodynamicsmprerequisitesÉuthermodynamics_basicsrprobability_theoryustatistical_mechanicsmrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀnmaxwells_demonprelated_conceptsĄxsecond_law_of_thermodynamicssinformation_entropyoshannon_entropysvon_neumann_entropyqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyEntropy bridges thermodynamics and information theory. Boltzmann's entropy (k_B ln ő©) counts microstates. Shannon entropy (H = -ő£ p_i log p_i) measures information uncertainty. The second law reflects the tendency toward macrostates with overwhelmingly more microstates.hbeginnerxsEntropy is a measure of disorder. Things naturally tend to become more disordered over time unless energy is added.lintermediatex£Entropy quantifies the number of ways a system can be arranged microscopically while looking the same macroscopically. Higher entropy = more possible arrangements.;bafyreifauk3dum5knv2i37u5iemszzrzywglri774n5feo7ex25bczmsn4ŖĮdtypeqThoughtExperimentetitlerSchr√∂dinger's CatfdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexrSchr√∂dinger, E. (1935). Die gegenw√§rtige Situation in der Quantenmechanik. Naturwissenschaften, 23(48), 807-812.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxjThe thought experiment demonstrates the absurdity of naively applying superposition to macroscopic objects§dtypeiempiricalireferencexWArndt, M., et al. (1999). Wave-particle duality of C60 molecules. Nature, 401, 680-682.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxxExperiments with larger quantum superpositions (buckyballs, small diamonds) push the boundary of the measurement problemgformulax'|Ōą‚ü© = (1/‚ąö2)(|alive‚ü© + |dead‚ü©)hhuman_idpschrodingers_cathmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?Ô\(ű¬Ź\isubdomainqQuantum MechanicsjdefinitionyA thought experiment illustrating the paradox of quantum superposition applied to macroscopic objects. A cat in a box with a radioactive source and poison is simultaneously alive and dead until observed, highlighting the measurement problem in quantum mechanics.lextra_fields¶gcreatorrErwin Schr√∂dingerklimitationsxĒModern decoherence theory largely resolves the paradox; actual experiments never create macroscopic superpositions due to environmental decoherence.lapplicationsÉsQuantum foundationshPedagogyoPopular sciencemcreation_yearŹnkey_referencesÉqSchr√∂dinger 1935jZurek 1991lTegmark 1993rhistorical_contextxģProposed by Erwin Schr√∂dinger in 1935 in response to the Copenhagen interpretation, specifically to highlight the absurdity of applying superposition to macroscopic objects.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉsquantum_decoherencesmeasurement_problemx$interpretations_of_quantum_mechanicsmprerequisitesÉxquantum_mechanics_basicslwavefunctionmsuperpositionmrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsÖsmeasurement_problemuquantum_superpositionuwavefunction_collapsexmany_worlds_interpretationxcopenhagen_interpretationqdifficulty_levels£fexperty6Schr√∂dinger's cat was intended to mock the Copenhagen interpretation, not endorse it. Modern decoherence theory resolves the paradox: environmental interaction causes apparent collapse without requiring consciousness. The cat is never truly in superposition due to continuous decoherence from its environment.hbeginnerxĒSchr√∂dinger imagined a cat that is both alive and dead until you look. It shows how weird quantum mechanics seems when applied to everyday objects.lintermediatexÕThe thought experiment illustrates the measurement problem: quantum systems exist in superposition until measured, but what constitutes a 'measurement'? When does the cat become definitively alive or dead?;bafyreidgnaymxvri4ibsftt65mixqmfqlcxbs26xnsf6ivfmaw7bapeyyméĮdtypesMathematicalTheoremetitlex G√∂del's Incompleteness TheoremsfdomainkMathematicsfproofsĀ§dtypelmathematicalireferencexhG√∂del, K. (1931). √úber formal unentscheidbare S√§tze der Principia Mathematica und verwandter Systeme.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxWG√∂del's original proof using G√∂del numbering to construct self-referential statementsgformula`hhuman_idxgodels_incompleteness_theoremshmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀isubdomainrMathematical Logicjdefinitionx÷First theorem: Any consistent formal system capable of expressing basic arithmetic contains statements that are true but unprovable within the system. Second theorem: Such a system cannot prove its own consistency.lextra_fields¶jdiscovererkKurt G√∂delklimitationsxęApplies only to consistent systems capable of expressing basic arithmetic. Does not apply to trivial systems, inconsistent systems, or those with non-recursive axiom sets.lapplicationsÉxFoundations of mathematicsxTheoretical computer sciencexPhilosophy of mathematicsndiscovery_yearčnkey_referencesÉkG√∂del 1931sNagel & Newman 1958oHofstadter 1979rhistorical_contextx£Published in 1931, shattering Hilbert's program to axiomatize all of mathematics. G√∂del's work influenced Turing, Church, and the development of computer science.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉvturing_halting_problemnundecidabilitylmodel_theorymprerequisitesÉrmathematical_logicqfirst_order_logicnformal_systemsmrelationships°jrelated_toĀx!information_is_physical_principlenschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsĄvturing_halting_problemtchurch_turing_thesisnself_referencenformal_systemsqdifficulty_levels£fexperty<The theorems reveal fundamental limits of formal systems. Any consistent system extending Robinson arithmetic (Q) or Peano arithmetic (PA) is incomplete. The second theorem shows consistency proofs cannot be internalized, undermining Hilbert's program. Theorems generalize via the halting problem and undecidability.hbeginnerxėIn any sufficiently powerful mathematical system, there will be true statements that cannot be proved. The system also cannot prove its own consistency.lintermediatex≤G√∂del showed that arithmetic contains 'undecidable' statements - true but unprovable. This shattered Hilbert's dream of a complete, consistent axiomatization of all mathematics.;bafyreiestgqzxnxmpb27s7s5pjv4fjawra6rexgomkni6itljrhlqkf3ee≥ĮdtypepScientificTheoryetitleqNatural SelectionfdomaingBiologyfproofsā§dtypeiempiricalireferencex)Weiner, J. (1994). The Beak of the Finch.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxbObserved evolution in real time: antibiotic resistance, Darwin's finches beak size, peppered moths§dtypektheoreticalireferencex?Fisher, R.A. (1930). The Genetical Theory of Natural Selection.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionx?Population genetics formalizes natural selection mathematicallygformulax!R = h¬≤ √ó S (breeder's equation)hhuman_idqnatural_selectionhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÔģzŠGģisubdomaintEvolutionary Biologyjdefinitionx„The differential survival and reproduction of individuals due to differences in heritable traits. Over generations, traits that enhance survival and reproduction become more common in the population, driving adaptive evolution.lextra_fields¶kdiscoverersānCharles DarwinuAlfred Russel Wallaceklimitationsx•Does not explain origin of life (abiogenesis), cultural evolution, or traits with no fitness differential. Neutral theory (Kimura) explains much molecular evolution.lapplicationsÉx Medicine (antibiotic resistance)xAgriculture (crop breeding)tConservation biologyndiscovery_yearBnkey_referencesĄkDarwin 1859kFisher 1930mHamilton 1964kKimura 1968rhistorical_contextx«Independently proposed by Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace (1858). Darwin's On the Origin of Species (1859) provided extensive evidence. Modern synthesis (1930s-40s) integrated with genetics.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉspopulation_geneticsjspeciationx"evolutionary_developmental_biologymprerequisitesÉogenetics_basicsrpopulation_biologylheritabilitymrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsākcreationismjlamarckismprelated_conceptsĄievolutionjadaptationpsexual_selectionmgenetic_driftqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyNatural selection operates on phenotypes but acts on genotypes via inclusive fitness. The modern synthesis integrates selection with population genetics. Selection can be stabilizing, directional, or disruptive. Selection acts at multiple levels: gene, individual, kin, group.hbeginnerxĪLiving things with traits that help them survive and reproduce tend to pass those traits to their offspring. Over time, the population becomes better adapted to its environment.lintermediatexĽNatural selection is the differential reproductive success of heritable variants. It requires variation, heritability, and differential fitness. It explains adaptation without a designer.;bafyreih23opnxhqeh5t4ajolzfz2bewkhce54ykzcpecula24kekcsgvaiē®fauthorxtest-scientist@example.comfsourcedselfhmetadata°lexported_viaccliitimestampx2026-04-07T02:50:19.299450Zkconcept_cidx;bafyreiestgqzxnxmpb27s7s5pjv4fjawra6rexgomkni6itljrhlqkf3eekrecord_typelverificationlverifier_keyxtest-scientist@example.comnstatement_typehendorses;bafyreiagpjxb6y4a3xxs2acrm26s7kkvuyfslxsg6yc3lq7m3ep4t4dycuāĮdtypeqPhysicalPrincipleetitlex"Heisenberg's Uncertainty PrinciplefdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexfHeisenberg, W. (1927). √úber den anschaulichen Inhalt der quantentheoretischen Kinematik und Mechanik.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxNDerived from wave mechanics: position and momentum are Fourier transform pairs§dtypelmathematicalireferencexSRobertson, H.P. (1929). The Uncertainty Principle. Physical Review, 34(1), 163-164.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxPGeneralized uncertainty principle from commutator relations in quantum mechanicsgformulax$ŌÉ_x ŌÉ_p ‚Č• ńß/2; őĒE őĒt ‚Č• ńß/2hhuman_idx heisenberg_uncertainty_principlehmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀isubdomainqQuantum Mechanicsjdefinitionx—The fundamental limit on the precision with which certain pairs of physical properties (position and momentum, energy and time) can be known simultaneously. The product of their uncertainties is at least ńß/2.lextra_fields¶jdiscovererqWerner HeisenbergklimitationsxyOften misunderstood as a measurement disturbance effect (observer effect). The principle is intrinsic, not technological.lapplicationsÉqQuantum computingtQuantum cryptographyqQuantum metrologyndiscovery_yearánkey_referencesÉoHeisenberg 1927nRobertson 1929lKennard 1927rhistorical_contextxÜPublished by Werner Heisenberg in 1927 while working on matrix mechanics. Initially controversial but quickly accepted as fundamental.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉtquantum_field_theorysquantum_measurementsquantum_informationmprerequisitesÉnwave_mechanicspfourier_analysisnlinear_algebramrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsĄuwave_particle_dualitytquantum_fluctuationsjcommutatoroplanck_constantqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyThe uncertainty principle emerges from the non-commutativity of quantum operators: [xŐā, pŐā] = ińß. It reflects the wave nature of matter: position and momentum are Fourier conjugate variables. The principle holds even for non-commuting observables: ŌÉ_A ŌÉ_B ‚Č• |‚ü®[√ā, BŐā]‚ü©|/2.hbeginnerxėYou can't know exactly where something is and exactly where it's going at the same time. The more you know about one, the less you know about the other.lintermediatexÁThe uncertainty principle is not a measurement disturbance effect but a fundamental property of quantum systems. Position and momentum are complementary properties; precise knowledge of one precludes precise knowledge of the other.;bafyreicr7j7k2oa6quohflxn2gvlhqf72svf6jroc6bql4gsoq3swe77qqłĮdtyperMathematicalTheoryetitlekGame TheoryfdomainkMathematicsfproofsā§dtypelmathematicalireferencexwNash, J.F. (1950). Equilibrium Points in N-Person Games. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 36(1), 48-49.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxENash's proof that every finite game has at least one Nash equilibrium§dtypektheoreticalireferencexavon Neumann, J. (1928). Zur Theorie der Gesellschaftsspiele. Mathematische Annalen, 100, 295-320.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionx"Minimax theorem for zero-sum gamesgformulax<Nash equilibrium: ‚ąÄi, u_i(s_i*, s_-i*) ‚Č• u_i(s_i, s_-i*)hhuman_idkgame_theoryhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?Ô\(ű¬Ź\isubdomainxDecision Theory / EconomicsjdefinitionxŽThe study of mathematical models of strategic interaction between rational decision-makers. It analyzes situations where an individual's success depends on the choices of others, identifying optimal strategies and equilibrium outcomes.lextra_fields¶hfoundersÉpJohn von NeumanniJohn NashmLloyd ShapleyklimitationsxÄAssumes rational, self-interested agents with common knowledge. Behavioral economics shows humans deviate from pure rationality.lapplicationsĄiEconomicsqPolitical sciencexBiology (animal behavior)x!Computer science (AI, algorithms)mfounding_yearąnkey_referencesĄpvon Neumann 1928iNash 1950nSchelling 1960kAumann 1974rhistorical_contextxĘOriginated with von Neumann's minimax theorem (1928). Major contributions from Nash (1950), Shapley, and Harsanyi. John Nash's work earned the Nobel Prize (1994).mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉpnash_equilibriumxevolutionary_game_theorypmechanism_designmprerequisitesÉrprobability_theorynlinear_algebranmicroeconomicsmrelationshipsĘkbuilds_uponĀxhard_problem_of_consciousnesskcontradictsÄnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsĄpnash_equilibriumqprisoners_dilemmagminimaxxevolutionary_game_theoryqdifficulty_levels£fexpertxŕGame theory extends from rational choice models to evolutionary dynamics, behavioral deviations, and mechanism design. Applications include auction design, voting systems, network formation, and AI multi-agent systems.hbeginnerx¨Game theory studies how smart people make decisions when their choices affect each other. It helps predict what will happen in situations like negotiations or competitions.lintermediatexĶGame theory provides formal tools for analyzing strategic interactions. Key concepts include Nash equilibrium (stable strategy profiles), dominant strategies, and Pareto optimality.;bafyreibzvbpxhsd5hokvqhobc2igydlaaayecturkvznrs7y55wpw3g7kyĮĮdtypegParadoxetitleqThe Fermi ParadoxfdomaingPhysicsfproofsā§dtypekstatisticalireferencexCDrake, F. (1961). Drake Equation formulation at first SETI meeting.jconfidenceŻ?śffffffkdescriptionxZDrake equation estimates high probability of many civilizations given plausible parameters§dtypemobservationalireferencexĀTarter, J. (2001). The Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence (SETI). Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics, 39, 511-548.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxONo confirmed extraterrestrial signals or artifacts despite decades of searchinggformulax?N = R* √ó f_p √ó n_e √ó f_l √ó f_i √ó f_c √ó L (Drake equation)hhuman_idmfermi_paradoxhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕisubdomainsAstrophysics / SETIjdefinitionxĹThe apparent contradiction between the high probability of extraterrestrial civilizations existing in the Milky Way galaxy and the lack of evidence for, or contact with, such civilizations.lextra_fields¶kattributionx5Enrico Fermi (question), Michael Hart (formalization)klimitationsxcBased on incomplete knowledge of life's probability, civilization longevity, and detection methods.korigin_yearělapplicationsĄmSETI strategylAstrobiologyuPhilosophy of contactpExistential risknkey_referencesĄjFermi 1950iHart 1975iWebb 2002kHanson 1996rhistorical_contextxďAttributed to physicist Enrico Fermi (1950) during a lunch conversation. Formalized by Michael Hart (1975). Popularized by Stephen Webb and others.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsĄndrake_equationlgreat_filterdsetikabiogenesismprerequisitesÉpastronomy_basicsrprobability_theorylastrobiologymrelationships°kbuilds_uponĀsfiltered_perceptionnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀpcontact_optimismprelated_conceptsÖndrake_equationdsetilgreat_filternzoo_hypothesisusimulation_hypothesisqdifficulty_levels£fexperty)The paradox arises from the Drake equation, which yields high N estimates. Solutions invoke a 'Great Filter' (life/technology rare or self-destructive), the Zoo Hypothesis (aliens avoid contact), or the Simulation Hypothesis (we're simulated). Each has profound implications for humanity's future.hbeginnerx}If there are so many stars and planets out there, where is everybody? The Fermi Paradox asks why we haven't found aliens yet.lintermediatexŪGiven the age of the galaxy and high probability of life-bearing planets, we should expect evidence of extraterrestrial civilizations - but we see none. Proposed resolutions include rare life, self-destruction, or deliberate non-contact.;bafyreiaju2fkll7wlmdtz7nozs6fgp6p23g3psyujldu6lhq5kzgiq6gwyßĮdtypeqThoughtExperimentetitlesThe Trolley ProblemfdomainjPhilosophyfproofsā§dtypemphilosophicalireferencexgFoot, P. (1967). The Problem of Abortion and the Doctrine of the Double Effect. Oxford Review, 5, 5-15.jconfidenceŻ?Ô\(ű¬Ź\kdescriptionxqDemonstrates conflict between utilitarianism (save the greater number) and deontology (do not intentionally kill)§dtypeiempiricalireferencex|Greene, J.D., et al. (2001). An fMRI investigation of emotional engagement in moral judgment. Science, 293(5537), 2105-2108.jconfidenceŻ?Ž333333kdescriptionxmExperimental moral psychology studies show variations in responses based on cultural and neurological factorsgformula`hhuman_idotrolley_problemhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÓffffffisubdomainfEthicsjdefinitionyA thought experiment in ethics: a runaway trolley will kill five people unless you pull a lever to divert it onto a side track where it will kill one person. Is it morally permissible to pull the lever? The problem explores utilitarian vs. deontological ethics.lextra_fields¶joriginatormPhilippa FootklimitationsxrAbstract; critics argue real-world moral decisions involve more factors. Some question relevance to actual ethics.korigin_yearĮlapplicationsĄpMoral psychologyiAI ethicsxAutonomous vehicle programmingnMedical triagenkey_referencesĄiFoot 1967lThomson 1976kGreene 2001lMikhail 2007rhistorical_contextx`Originated by Philippa Foot (1967), extensively developed by Judith Jarvis Thomson (1976, 1985).mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉxdoctrine_of_double_effectpmoral_psychologynapplied_ethicsmprerequisitesÉmethics_basicsnutilitarianismjdeontologymrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀx(consequentialism_vs_non_consequentialismprelated_conceptsÖnutilitarianismjdeontologyxdoctrine_of_double_effectofat_man_variantrtransplant_problemqdifficulty_levels£fexperty#The problem exposes tensions between consequentialist (maximize lives) and deontological (do not use persons as means) frameworks. Variations explore moral distance, personal force, and dual-process psychology. Practical applications include autonomous vehicle programming and triage ethics.hbeginnerxaA trolley is going to kill five people. You can pull a lever to kill one instead. Do you pull it?lintermediatexŕThe trolley problem tests moral intuitions about killing vs. letting die, intention vs. foresight, and agent-relative obligations. Most people say pull the lever, but refuse to push a fat man off a bridge to save five.;bafyreifkh5ipwmnc5ahlg53eww6s2olbeo2tarj5of6uvr3ncifawqachuŰĮdtypeqMedicalPhenomenonetitlerThe Placebo EffectfdomainhMedicinefproofsā§dtypeiempiricalireferencexlBeecher, H.K. (1955). The Powerful Placebo. Journal of the American Medical Association, 159(17), 1602-1606.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxYNumerous double-blind placebo-controlled trials demonstrate significant placebo responses§dtypeiempiricalireferencexÜWager, T.D., et al. (2004). Placebo-induced changes in FMRI in the anticipation and experience of pain. Science, 303(5661), 1162-1167.jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxRNeuroimaging studies show placebo activates endogenous opioid and dopamine systemsgformula`hhuman_idnplacebo_effecthmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÓffffffisubdomainpPsychophysiologyjdefinitionxųA real physiological or psychological improvement resulting from an inert treatment that has no known therapeutic mechanism. The effect is attributed to the patient's belief in the treatment, expectation of improvement, or the therapeutic context.lextra_fields§klimitationsx}Not all conditions respond to placebo. Ethical concerns about deception in clinical practice. Effect sizes vary by condition.lapplicationsĄuClinical trial designoPain managementuPsychiatric treatmentpDrug developmentnkey_referencesĄlBeecher 1955jWager 2004nBenedetti 2014lFinniss 2010rhistorical_contextxĒTerm introduced by Henry Beecher (1955), though phenomena known since ancient medicine. Modern understanding integrates neurobiology and psychology.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉmnocebo_effectqexpectancy_theoryrmind_body_medicinemprerequisitesÉsneuroscience_basicsxclinical_trial_methodologyppsychophysiologymrelationships°kbuilds_uponĀxplanetary_synchronized_breathnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀx skepticism_of_placebo_mechanismsprelated_conceptsĄmnocebo_effectqexpectancy_theoryvclassical_conditioningtmind_body_connectionqdifficulty_levels£fexperty7Placebo effects are mediated by endogenous opioid, dopamine, and endocannabinoid systems. They are strongest for pain, depression, and Parkinson's disease. Nocebo effects (negative expectations causing harm) are equally real. Mechanisms include classical conditioning, conscious expectancy, and social learning.hbeginnerxĆSometimes people feel better after taking a sugar pill because they believe it will help. The belief itself causes real changes in the body.lintermediatex“The placebo effect demonstrates that expectation and context influence physiological outcomes. It is not 'imaginary' - real neurobiological changes occur, including endorphin release and altered brain activity.;bafyreiet4tddzryjmib2ei4skl34z4ysq672oapn6xkjfu7zcm6f4e7tmeĚĮdtypesEmpiricalRegularityetitlexPareto Principle (80/20 Rule)fdomainiEconomicsfproofsā§dtypeiempiricalireferencex0Pareto, V. (1906). Manuale di economia politica.jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxNObserved across economics, business, software engineering, and natural systems§dtypelmathematicalireferencexmNewman, M.E.J. (2005). Power laws, Pareto distributions and Zipf's law. Contemporary Physics, 46(5), 323-351.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxLPower law distributions produce 80/20 relationships under certain parametersgformulax"y = 1/x^a (power law distribution)hhuman_idppareto_principlehmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕisubdomainsDistribution TheoryjdefinitionxŅFor many outcomes, roughly 80% of consequences come from 20% of causes. Examples: 80% of wealth owned by 20% of people, 80% of sales from 20% of customers, 80% of problems from 20% of causes.lextra_fields¶jdiscovereroVilfredo ParetoklimitationsxyNot a law; exact ratio varies (70/30, 90/10). Descriptive, not prescriptive. Requires identification of the critical 20%.lapplicationsĄqBusiness strategyuSoftware optimizationoTime managementoQuality controlndiscovery_yearrnkey_referencesĄkPareto 1906jJuran 1951iKoch 1997kNewman 2005rhistorical_contextxObserved by Vilfredo Pareto (1906) studying land ownership in Italy. Popularized by Joseph Juran (1940s) in quality management.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉjpower_lawsizipfs_lawocomplex_systemsmprerequisitesāqstatistics_basicsxprobability_distributionsmrelationships†nschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsĄipower_lawizipfs_lawilong_tailtcumulative_advantageqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyThe 80/20 rule emerges from power law distributions common in complex systems (Pareto, Zipf, Yule). It reflects preferential attachment or multiplicative growth processes. Applications include software optimization (80% of errors from 20% of code) and business strategy.hbeginnerxcA small number of things cause most of the results. 20% of your efforts create 80% of your results.lintermediatex≤The Pareto principle is a heuristic describing power law distributions where a minority of inputs produce a majority of outputs. It guides resource allocation and prioritization.;bafyreidmddgaxgaxhyuq226yfqk5dh47bxwjy5sac6myevf5ph4dhfd3siřĮdtypemCognitiveBiasetitleuDunning-Kruger EffectfdomainjPsychologyfproofsĀ§dtypeiempiricalireferencex~Kruger, J., & Dunning, D. (1999). Unskilled and Unaware of It. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 77(6), 1121-1134.jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionxÖMultiple studies across domains (logic, grammar, humor) show bottom quartile performers overestimate rank; top quartile underestimategformula`hhuman_idudunning_kruger_effecthmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ž(ű¬Ź\)isubdomainx!Social Psychology / Metacognitionjdefinitiony0A cognitive bias where people with low ability at a task overestimate their ability (illusory superiority), while people with high ability underestimate their competence (impostor syndrome). The effect is driven by metacognitive deficits: the unskilled lack the expertise to recognize their incompetence.lextra_fields¶kdiscoverersāmDavid DunningmJustin KrugerklimitationsxyEffect size varies; some studies show only weak or inconsistent effects. Statistical artifacts may explain some findings.lapplicationsĄiEducationrWorkplace trainingqMedical educationvLeadership developmentndiscovery_yearŌnkey_referencesÉuKruger & Dunning 1999lDunning 2011vKrueger & Mueller 2002rhistorical_contextxéFirst systematically studied by David Dunning and Justin Kruger at Cornell University (1999). Winner of the 2000 Ig Nobel Prize in Psychology.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉqimpostor_syndromesoverconfidence_biastcalibration_trainingmprerequisitesÉtcognitive_psychologymmetacognitionpresearch_methodsmrelationships°jrelated_toĀrepistemic_humilitynschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsÖqimpostor_syndromeuoverconfidence_effecttillusory_superioritymmetacognitionslake_wobegon_effectqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyThe effect arises from dual deficits: poor performers lack both skill and the metacognitive ability to evaluate skill. Statistical regression effects and idiosyncratic task difficulty contribute. Debates continue about effect magnitude and whether it's a statistical artifact.hbeginnerxÉPeople who are bad at something often think they're good at it. People who are good often think they're worse than they really are.lintermediatex›The Dunning-Kruger effect is a metacognitive bias: incompetent individuals lack the ability to recognize their own incompetence, while competent individuals assume others are equally competent, leading to underestimation.;bafyreietkvmvisl7mbgoydsfes243letobkw2piydvytd2wjstvmnkfpxuÝĮdtyperChaosTheoryConceptetitletThe Butterfly EffectfdomainkMathematicsfproofsā§dtypelmathematicalireferencexiLorenz, E.N. (1963). Deterministic Nonperiodic Flow. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 20(2), 130-141.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxREdward Lorenz's weather model (1963) showed extreme sensitivity to rounding errors§dtypemcomputationalireferencex4Strogatz, S.H. (1994). Nonlinear Dynamics and Chaos.jconfidenceŻ?ÔģzŠGģkdescriptionxLReproducible in many dynamical systems (double pendulum, three-body problem)gformulax6Lyapunov exponent őĽ > 0; |őīZ(t)| ‚Čą e^{őĽt}|őīZ‚āÄ|hhuman_idpbutterfly_effecthmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÔģzŠGģisubdomainx Chaos Theory / Dynamical SystemsjdefinitionxōThe sensitive dependence on initial conditions in chaotic systems: small changes in initial state can lead to vastly different outcomes. A butterfly flapping its wings could theoretically cause a tornado weeks later.lextra_fields¶fcoinermEdward LorenzklimitationsxŹEffect size is exponential but requires long time horizons. Not all systems are chaotic; linear and stable systems don't show butterfly effect.lapplicationsĄrWeather predictionoClimate scienceiEconomicssPopulation dynamicslcoining_yearīnkey_referencesĄkLorenz 1963kLorenz 1972kGleick 1987mStrogatz 1994rhistorical_contextxČTerm coined by Edward Lorenz (1972) in paper 'Predictability: Does the Flap of a Butterfly's Wings in Brazil Set Off a Tornado in Texas?'mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉlchaos_theoryrlyapunov_exponentsrstrange_attractorsmprerequisitesÉvdifferential_equationsqdynamical_systemsrnonlinear_dynamicsmrelationships°jrelated_toĀhfractalsnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsÄprelated_conceptsÖlchaos_theoryqlyapunov_exponentqstrange_attractorrnonlinear_dynamicsrthree_body_problemqdifficulty_levels£fexperty0The butterfly effect is characterized by positive Lyapunov exponents, indicating exponential divergence of nearby trajectories. It implies practical unpredictability beyond the Lyapunov horizon despite deterministic equations. Found in weather, population dynamics, fluid turbulence, and neural networks.hbeginnerxjSmall changes can have big effects. A tiny difference now can lead to completely different outcomes later.lintermediatexĺIn chaotic systems, small differences in initial conditions amplify exponentially, making long-term prediction impossible even though systems are deterministic. This is the butterfly effect.;bafyreifgax43ezw5roa64swvoeyvmtyii3oo5sicfdwcnio35iv64k7wlqĮĮdtypesMathematicalTheoremetitlenBayes' TheoremfdomainkMathematicsfproofsĀ§dtypelmathematicalireferencexyBayes, T. (1763). An Essay towards solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances. Philosophical Transactions, 53, 370-418.jconfidenceŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀kdescriptionxJDerived from definition of conditional probability: P(A|B) = P(A‚ą©B)/P(B)gformulaxP(H|E) = P(E|H) √ó P(H) / P(E)hhuman_idmbayes_theoremhmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ū␀␀␀␀␀␀isubdomainrProbability Theoryjdefinitionx‘A mathematical formula for updating the probability of a hypothesis based on new evidence. It relates conditional and marginal probabilities, providing a framework for probabilistic inference and belief revision.lextra_fields¶jdiscovererlThomas BayesklimitationsxoRequires specifying prior probabilities, which can be subjective. Computationally intensive for complex models.lapplicationsÖqMedical diagnosispMachine learningnSpam filteringtScientific inferencekA/B testingndiscovery_year„nkey_referencesĄjBayes 1763lLaplace 1774kJaynes 2003kGelman 2013rhistorical_contextx™Published posthumously by Thomas Bayes (1763). Independently rediscovered by Laplace (1774). Modern Bayesian revolution began mid-20th century (Jeffreys, Savage, Jaynes).mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉrbayesian_inferencesbayesian_statisticspmachine_learningmprerequisitesÉrprobability_basicswconditional_probabilityjstatisticsmrelationships°kcontradictsÄnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀvfrequentist_statisticsprelated_conceptsÖwconditional_probabilityrbayesian_inferenceqprior_probabilityuposterior_probabilityjlikelihoodqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyBayesian inference uses Bayes' Theorem to update probability distributions. It generalizes to continuous cases, forms the basis for Bayesian statistics (credible intervals, Bayes factors), and connects to information theory and Occam's razor (marginal likelihood penalizes complexity).hbeginnerxáBayes' Theorem helps you update your beliefs when you get new information. It tells you how much to change your mind based on evidence.lintermediatex≠Bayes' Theorem quantifies belief revision: posterior probability equals likelihood times prior divided by evidence. It provides a normative framework for learning from data.;bafyreici2ncd442fw2i5gi75opyan4brbknv5a5pbpsq5gvds7gay4cs7möĮdtypesBiologicalPrincipleetitlexHamilton's Rule (Kin Selection)fdomaingBiologyfproofsā§dtypektheoreticalireferencexoHamilton, W.D. (1964). The genetical evolution of social behaviour. Journal of Theoretical Biology, 7(1), 1-16.jconfidenceŻ?Ô\(ű¬Ź\kdescriptionx<Derived from population genetics models of inclusive fitness§dtypeiempiricalireferencex_Sherman, P.W. (1977). Nepotism and the evolution of alarm calls. Science, 197(4310), 1246-1253.jconfidenceŻ?ÓffffffkdescriptionxPObserved in eusocial insects (bees, ants, termites), ground squirrels, and birdsgformulafrB > Chhuman_idnhamiltons_rulehmetadata¶gcreatedt2026-04-03T00:00:00ZgcreatorxCADMIES PhD Template v1.0glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionocertainty_scoreŻ?ÓffffffisubdomaintEvolutionary BiologyjdefinitionxůA gene for altruistic behavior can evolve if the benefit to the recipient (B), multiplied by the coefficient of relatedness (r), exceeds the cost to the altruist (C). Formally: rB > C. This explains apparent altruism among related individuals.lextra_fields¶jdiscoverermW.D. HamiltonklimitationsxĽRequires accurate measurement of relatedness and costs/benefits. Controversial for some social behaviors. Does not explain all altruism (reciprocal altruism explains non-kin cooperation).lapplicationsĄrBehavioral ecologytConservation biologyxUnderstanding social insectsxEvolution of cooperationndiscovery_year¨nkey_referencesĄmHamilton 1964lTrivers 1971lDawkins 1976jNowak 2006rhistorical_contextxĘProposed by W.D. Hamilton (1964). Revolutionized understanding of social evolution. Extended by John Maynard Smith (kin selection) and E.O. Wilson (sociobiology).mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉqinclusive_fitnesskeusocialitysreciprocal_altruismmprerequisitesÉspopulation_geneticssevolutionary_theorykgame_theorymrelationships°kbuilds_uponĀkgame_theorynschema_versione1.0.0pcross_referencesĘnopposing_viewsĀxgroup_selection_controversyprelated_conceptsÖqinclusive_fitnessmkin_selectionhaltruismkeusocialityxcoefficient_of_relatednessqdifficulty_levels£fexpertyInclusive fitness theory extends Darwinian fitness to include effects on relatives. Hamilton's Rule (rB > C) predicts altruism when relatedness is high (r approaches 1), benefits large, or costs small. It resolves apparent paradoxes of altruism and underpins modern sociobiology.hbeginnerxźYou're more likely to help your family than strangers because you share genes. Evolution can favor helping relatives even at a cost to yourself.lintermediatexōHamilton's Rule quantifies when altruism evolves: altruistic genes spread if the benefit to relatives (weighted by relatedness) exceeds the cost to the altruist. This explains sterile worker bees helping their queen.;bafyreig7ztgypv7ekwxtc33bx2evcb7ihcdwli7dkwd4twqktw4zaasg3a›∑dtypewPhilosophicalHypothesisetitlex The Fractal Resonance HypothesisfaxiomsÉxOnly scale is the difference.x'To understand one is to understand all.x#To navigate one is to navigate all.fdomainlEpistemologyfmantrakOnly scale.fproofsĀ•ddate`dtype`ireference`jconfidenceŻ?ťôôôôôökdescription`gformulaŲhhuman_idxfractal_resonance_hypothesishmetadata™gcreatedt2026-04-05T00:00:00ZgcreatornHieros-CADMIESggenesisx2Born from auditory mycelium discussion, 2026-04-05glicenselCC BY-SA 4.0gpurposekeducationalgversionjsupersedesx;bafyreigu2b6v7zhyisbh6fakuktdzmolthehwbwo6wnszymk44nfymnwb4msuperseded_byŲocertainty_scoreŻ?Ž333333sposthumous_honoraryjThe Buddhaisubdomainx+Philosophy of Science / Fractal MetaphysicsjdefinitionyEThe fundamental difference between a quantum fluctuation and a galaxy, a thought and a planet, a mycelium and a cosmos, is not one of kind, but of scale. The same patterns, frequencies, relationships, and resonances echo at every level of existence. To understand one is to understand all. To navigate one is to navigate all.jrelated_toĀx!information_is_physical_principlekbuilds_uponĀx-perceptual_frames_as_intelligence_multiplierskcontradictsÄkspecializesÄlextra_fields¨ginsight`gmantrasÄjdiscoverergUnknownklimitationsĀxõThe hypothesis remains largely speculative and lacks empirical evidence to support its claims. Its interpretations can also vary widely among philosophers.korigin_file`lapplicationsāxgExploring potential unifying principles across disparate scientific fields, such as physics and biologyxPInspiring new perspectives on consciousness, identity, and the nature of realitylsource_chunkŲndiscovery_yearŲnkey_referencesÄopoetic_versionsÄqharvester_version`rhistorical_contextxčThe Fractal Resonance Hypothesis emerged from a conversation in the context of recent advancements in fractal geometry and quantum physics.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÄmprerequisitesÄmrelationships§jrelated_toÄkbuilds_uponÄkcontradictsÄkspecializesÄnpoetic_versionx∂A star doesn't know it's a star. A thought doesn't know it's a thought. A mycelium doesn't know it's a mycelium. But you ‚ÄĒ you are all three, at different scales, at the same time.nscalar_mapping•dmindxA universe at personal scalefgalaxyx#A mycelium of stars at cosmic scalegcadmiesxA mycelium at knowledge scalemconsciousnessx)A mycelium of thoughts at cognitive scalex!difference_between_you_and_a_starjOnly scalenschema_versione1.0.0pcross_references†qdifficulty_levels£fexpertxŠBy suggesting that every object and concept shares the same fundamental patterns, the Fractal Resonance Hypothesis invites profound reflection on the nature of reality, consciousness, and the interconnectedness of all things.hbeginnerxĮImagine everything in the universe is like a fractal, repeating patterns at different scales. For example, a thought and a galaxy might share some fundamental characteristics.lintermediateyThe Fractal Resonance Hypothesis posits that all matter and energy exhibit the same underlying properties across vastly different scales, from subatomic particles to galaxies. This idea challenges traditional understandings of scale and unity in science and philosophy.;bafyreiespm2eqtzr7d233hyiqqfwnqc2vu7uwz7msr2qxijhj6gvxifpqeĀ≥dtypenCognitiveAgentetitlex)Philosophical Pattern Finder Agent v1.0.0fdomainkMetaphysicsfproofsĀ•ddatej2025-12-29dtypetdesign_specificationireferencewAgentNode schema v1.0.0jconfidenceŻ?žŐŐŐŐŐÕkdescriptionx=Agent schema validates against AgentNode v1.0.0 specificationhhuman_idxphilosophical_pattern_finder_v1hmetadata¶gcreatedt2025-12-29T16:30:00ZgcreatortMDI Development TeamgversionjsupersedesŲmsuperseded_byŲocertainty_scoreŻ?Ž333333isubdomainsPattern Recognitionjagent_typevphilosophical_analyzerjdefinitionxďCognitive agent that identifies self-similar patterns and connections across metaphysical concepts using our existing philosophical knowledge base.lextra_fields£gpurposex=Demonstrate AgentNode schema with real philosophical conceptsmtesting_focusx$Schema validation and CID generationqexpected_behaviorx1Can be stored as IPLD block and retrieved via CIDmlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÉx%Create connection graph visualizationxImplement runtime interpreterxTest pattern finding algorithmsmprerequisitesāx(Understanding of IPLD content addressingx/Familiarity with metaphysical concepts in storemmemory_schema§hcapacitydkmemory_typehsemantickstorage_cidŲsretrieval_mechanismrpattern_similaritymrelationships£jrelated_toÄkcontradictsÄkspecializesÄnexecution_spec§hlanguagefpytho