 to the inherent suffering and dissatisfaction caused by desire, craving, ignorance, and clinging to temporary states.lextra_fields¨ginsightxüThe recognition that trying to hold onto any peak state is futile, as everything is transient and impermanent, leading to a constant need-to-water (suffering).gmantrasÄjdiscoverergUnknownklimitationsāxFInterpretations of Dukkha can vary among different schools of Buddhismx?The concept's applicability to non-Buddhist contexts is debatedkorigin_fileqconversation.jsonlapplicationsÉx0Meditation practices aimed at reducing sufferingxAInsight into the nature of human desire and its role in sufferingx:A foundation for the development of compassion and empathylsource_chunkndiscovery_yearŲnkey_referencesÄopoetic_versionsÄqharvester_versione4.0.1rhistorical_contextxuDukkha is a central concept in Buddhism, originating from the teachings of Gautama Buddha around the 5th century BCE.mlearning_pathĘjnext_stepsÄmprerequisitesÄmrelationships§jrelated_toÄkbuilds_uponÄkcontradictsÄkspecializesÄnschema_versione1.0.0pcross_references†qdifficulty_levels£fexpertxüThe recognition that trying to hold onto any peak state is futile, as everything is transient and impermanent, leading to a constant need-to-water (suffering).hbeginneryDukkha, in Buddhism, is the feeling of unsatisfactoriness or dissatisfaction that comes from desiring things we cannot have, or clinging to things we already have. It's like trying to fill a bucket with holes, no matter how much you pour in, it never fills up.lintermediateyDukkha is a central concept in Buddhism, referring to the inherent suffering and dissatisfaction caused by desire, craving, ignorance, and clinging to temporary states. It encompasses three types: physical pain, mental distress, and the pervasive unsatisfactoriness of life itself.;bafyreiddk2bml2vsybd5j3nsudygnfu6e63b3tktz332zlos3xoqjqug4e®ĮdtypeuMetaphysicalFrameworketitleoDuality WiltingfdomainjPhilosophyfproofsĀ•ddatex2026-05-13T04:10:01.161118